ons":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe adrenal glands develop from two distinct embryological origins. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eintermediate mesoderm near the gonadal ridge\u003C/strong\u003E gives rise to the adrenal cortex, which develops first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeural crest cells from the trunk region\u003C/strong\u003E migrate into the developing cortex to form the adrenal medulla, not the cortex\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELateral plate mesoderm\u003C/strong\u003E forms the body wall, limb buds and cardiovascular system\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurface ectoderm near the neural tube\u003C/strong\u003E forms the epidermis and its derivatives\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPosterior foregut endoderm\u003C/strong\u003E forms the digestive tract and associated organs\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe fetal adrenal cortex is proportionally much larger than in adults and produces steroid hormones essential for maintaining pregnancy. After birth, the fetal cortex regresses and is replaced by the definitive adult cortex.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The adrenal cortex develops from intermediate mesoderm near the gonadal ridge during embryological development.","The adrenal medulla forms from neural crest cells that migrate into the developing cortex.","The fetal adrenal cortex is proportionally larger than in adults and produces steroid hormones essential for pregnancy."],"references":["Nicolaides NC, Willenberg HS, Bornstein SR, et al. Adrenal Cortex: Embryonic Development, Anatomy, Histology and Physiology. In: Feingold KR, Anawalt B, Blackman MR, et al., editors. Endotext [Internet]. South Dartmouth (MA): MDText.com, Inc. Updated 2023 Jun 12. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK278945/#","Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56974"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15818"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56974"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T18:09:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T18:10:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8509"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71465"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4929"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6d","name":"Endocrine","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50